To everyone who is asking about the soundtrack used in the Bleeding Darkness performance of Jungwon and Ni-ki in MIX&MAX, yes it is a remix of three songs. In the first half, lyrics of Too Far Gone by ARTY and NK were used. Also, "I wanna end this" said by Ni-ki was inspired by Bury a Friend by Billie Eilish (original lyrics were "I wanna end me"). On the other hand, "Bite me" said by Jungwon was an additional line to the soundtrack. The soundtrack without the lyrics of Bury a Friend was used in the first half. During the dance break or when Jungwon changed his outfit from the white costume to the red and black, the song Momma I Hit A Lick by 2 Chainz and Kendrick Lamar was used. The audio itself without the lyrics was used.

I hope Studio Choom will consider giving both these talented kids an opportunity to guest in AOTM.   It's the perfect opportunity for Ni-ki to showcase his talent, skill, and expertise in dancing. It would be wonderful to see him explore and tackle varying dance styles in his performance.  With Jungwon, what this performance lacked was the opportunity for him to showcase how clean and sharp of a dancer he truly is. I would love to see a performance with him showcasing his excellent popping skills, as well as his ability to express emotions through his facial expressions.  Both boys are wonderful and harmonious together, but I believe they have the capability to shine and flourish individually as well.   I would love to see these two on here again for more performances, whether that'd be together as a unit or as individual performers.

Road to 5M
I was extremely excited but also very concerned when the trailer came out. They're two incredibly talented dancers and artists, and they've done incredible things but what this performance stands for its deeply worrying. You can tell they're passionate, so they own the music and everything, but you can also tell that it's not their music (yes, I know they didn't sing it/record it, etc.) but it doesn't seem like THEIR music, like it was forced on them. It's representing the dark forces of the industry and those who would distort innocence and talent for their own profit. Knowing the history of what K-pop idols have suffered at the hands of their companies, schedules, etc. it's a perfectly terrifying metaphor for an innocent, passionate soul being crushed and turned into one of its own by the massive jaws of materialism, workaholism, and even satanism. Yes, I went there, look at the symbolism used and it makes sense. To be clear, I love and support Enhypen, they're one of my top favorite groups and part of the reason is their relative innocence as artists, but this video as a metaphor for what they could be turned into scares me. Please let me know your thoughts on the matter, I think it's something that needs to be discussed and I could be saying all of this erroneously, please let me know your thoughts again. :)

imagine setting the standards THAT high at the young age of 16 and 18 (international), and only ni-ki and jungwon can relate.   the concept they went for is not an easy one at all. the dark and gorey concept was delivered in such an exceptional level. you need to embody the character needed for the performance and that's what both ni-ki and jungwon did so perfectly. their expressions were beyond satisfactory. they were so captivating, so appropriate, and are even perfection, and they also maintained being in their characters which is what i would like to applaud them for.   they're always able to maintain that character and that energy in every performance they get. i'm so grateful we got the chance to see two of the powerful dancers, if not the most powerful and the best, of this generation. as someone who watched them in i-land, i've always longed to see them in one unit performance together because i believe that having the two together would make a powerful stage. they both have different styles but they compliment each other so well. they both have powerful moves but are so well-calculated and well-executed. their moves are so clean and so controlled. they are truly such outstanding performers.   ni-ki once again proved himself that he's the 4th gen dance prodigy. his body lines are beautiful and amazing as always. his moves are so clean yet so powerful. and this is one of the performances that makes me proud because looking back at his i-land focuses and comparing it to this, you can see how much he improved, especially with his expressions. he was already a powerful dancer back then but he keeps on improving himself day by day.   as for jungwon, as we all know from i-land, he's the BEST in popping. we can really see that and i swear his movements are insanely captivating. his isolations and pops are always so on point, it's actually crazy to think that he's that great at such a young age. and like ni-ki, he really proves himself that he's an amazing dancer and he keeps on improving as day passes. also, i'd love to point out how he knows how expressive his eyes are and he knows how to use his assets well.   never would i ever thought that we'd get this stage. from going against each other as dance representatives from their respective units and not being able to be in a unit together to finally dancing in one unit together and showing everyone how well they go with each other.   and i have to say this, they're the best dancers. and i swear, these two's range is limitless. this is only a glimpse of the whole entirety of what they can offer. we are never gonna be ready for them.

A WON-KI SUBUNIT I NEVER KNEW I NEEDED
I think most people wouldn't look at the dance's meaning but it's actually really deep. If we give the dance into some thought, jungwon was trying to escape ni-ki's grip. the dance is very powerful, it displays how painful pain was inflicted to jungwon, and at first he looked like was "hostaged" so ni-ki could bite him (one of the reasons he was in pain) one of the other reasons he was in pain was because he couldn't see ni-ki at first especially because he was "hiding in the darkness." (from the lyrics) in the first parts of the dance ni-ki was always behind jungwon, he was hurting him from behind and when jungwon realized it was ni-ki he knew how painful he can hurt him. despite jungwon being aware by the pain being inflicted to him, he decides to tell ni-ki "fight me" but ni-ki was stubborn and wanted to fight jungwon, so he said "i wanted to end this" two more times, probably torturing jungwon's character in him, making the evil rise in him. at the end, jungwon's clothes turned from white to black and red. at the first parts of the dance ni-ki wore white, but he had black and red  inflicted towards the end of the clothing, maybe that is one of the reasons why ni-ki was slowly turning evil. I felt like ni-ki and jungwon interfered with something, they both were pure souls but they got interfered by something evil. the thing that probably triggered to be evil and the one who gave in first was ni-ki, but then slowly jungwon gave in too. They both were probably in pain, that's why ni-ki hid and bit jungwon so he could end everything. at the end, the pure souls ended up as evil souls. I honestly think there is more into the dance that I can't explain, it's so well choreographed and the boys interpreted the theme very well.
